","1296–Male":"1296–Deceased","1287–1336":"1287–1336","1235–Male":"1235–Deceased","1239–Female":"1239–Deceased","1239":"1239","1336":"1336","1269":"1269","1235":"1235","1299":"1299","1287":"1287","1296":"1296","1273":"1273","1309":"1309","Cathcart, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Cathcart, Renfrewshire, Scotland","Cathcart, Renfrewshire":"Cathcart, Renfrewshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cathcart","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Cathcart (Renfrewshire)."],"variants":[{"name":"Kithcart","meanings":["English: variant of   Cathcart  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William Cathcart 5th Laird Cathcart was born in 1269, his father, William Cathcart 4th Laird Cathcart, was 35 and his mother, Margaret Hendry, was 30. He married Margaret Wallace in 1299, in Cathcart, Renfrewshire, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1309, at the age of 40."},"et":{"1269–1309":"1269–1309","1273–Female":"1273–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1296–Male":"1296–Surnud","1287–1336":"1287–1336","1235–Male":"1235–Surnud","1239–Female":"1239–Surnud","1239":"1239","1336":"1336","1269":"1269","1235":"1